sec.p:
Approximately 70 participants attended over the day-and-a-half long event, drawing participants from 16 countries around the world, thereby ensuring opportunities for cross-cultural aspects to enhance the experience. The dual themes of the Conference were ‘Researching Nursing Ethics’ and ‘The Ethics of Research’. The conference comprised eight plenary sessions (two open to the public) and three parallel sessions during which 30 papers were presented. The papers presented ranged over diverse aspects of nursing ethics and research topics/projects and ensured that the objectives of the Conference were met, namely:


strengthening interaction/networking of researchers, teachers, practitioners and students in nursing and healthcare ethics;



developing international dialogue around ethics and research;



providing an opportunity to reflect critically on nursing ethics as a developing discipline;



anticipating and preparing for ethical challenges in health and social care research in a global context.
